body:
From the source code provided in this ticked (attached file).

With a class [Player] having a constructor Player([string]p1)
And with another class [Game] with a method SetScoreForPlayer([Player]$p1, [int]p2) { ... }
When calling method SetScoreForPlayer("p1", p2) from an instance of [Game] where p1 is of type [string] but first param from SetScoreForPlayer([Player]$p1, [int]p2) is of type [Player]
Then the runtime call the constructor of [Player], passing the string value of "p1" to it.

There is no reason why $aGame.SetScoreForPlayer("p1", p2) should call [Player]'s constructor.


With $p1 = [Player]::new("Jhon")
If I call  SetScoreForPlayer(p1, p2)
Where p1 is of the right type (of [Player])
Then the code will work as expected.

Please refer to the attached source file: [Bug.zip](https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/files/6658267/Bug.zip)


Extracted source code example:


```
class Player {
    [string]$Name
    [int]$Score = 0

    Player([string]$name){
        $this.Name = $name
    }
}

class Game{
    [Player[]]$Players = @()

    [string]SetScoreForPlayer([Player]$player, [int]$score){
        foreach ($player in $this.Players) {
            if ($player.Name -eq $player.Name) {
                $player.Score = $score
            }
        }
        throw "Player $($player.Name) aren't playing in this game"
    }
}



$p = [Player]::new("Jhon")

$game = [Game]::new()
$game.Players += $p


write-host "Here is $($game.SetScoreForPlayer("$p", 3))"


```
